<title>Paper Scout Research Report - 2026-07-23</title>

<p>This run covered the 2026-07-20 to 2026-07-23 Hugging Face pool (103 papers) and went deep on three threads. The headline finding is about <b>evidence quality, not results</b>. <b>Xiaomi-Robotics-1</b> claims VLA scaling from 100K hours of UMI trajectories — our table-level audit shows the benchmark numbers are real (one is already leaderboard-verified), but the scaling curves that carry the paper's thesis stop at 20K hours, and the "crucial" auto-labeling pipeline is never ablated. <b>Masked Visual Actions</b> turns a video model into a forward/inverse dynamics model with a 15-hour LoRA — our weight-level probe of the released adapters shows exactly where that interface lives in the network, and exactly how thin the policy-evaluation evidence is (a 7-point correlation). And a three-paper cluster on <b>long-horizon interactive world models</b> (ABot-World-0, AlayaWorld, Self Gradient Forcing) turned out to be one coherent stack: four distinct diagnoses of drift, four composable fixes — with the uncomfortable common gap that nobody measures identity or controllability decay past one minute.</p>

<callout emoji="✅" background-color="light-green">
  <p><b>Standout:</b> the drift-mechanisms cluster is the most buildable finding of the period. SGF's two-pass training (code released same-day, Apache-2.0) supervises how context is <i>written</i> into the KV cache — a gap Self Forcing leaves open — and it bolts cleanly onto ABot-World-0's causal student, whose 5B weights already run at 720p/16FPS on a single consumer GPU. The composability map below is directly actionable.</p>
</callout>

<h1>VLA progress this week is alignment and data, not architecture</h1>

<p>No new VLA architecture showed up in this pool. What showed up instead: frame alignment (robot-centric pointmaps), representation alignment during finetuning, semantic-geometric decoupling for grasping, two egocentric data releases, and one very large data-scale bet from Xiaomi. The field is currently spending its effort fixing what behavior cloning breaks and feeding models more real trajectories — which makes the Xiaomi paper the right thing to audit closely.</p>

<h2>Xiaomi-Robotics-1: the numbers are real, the scaling story is thinner than the title</h2>
<p>Guo et al. (Xiaomi, 2026) · <a href="https://huggingface.co/papers/2607.15330">HF</a> · <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2607.15330">PDF</a> · <a href="https://robotics.xiaomi.com/xiaomi-robotics-1.html">Project</a> · <a href="https://github.com/XiaomiRobotics/Xiaomi-Robotics-1">Repo (README only)</a></p>

<p>The paper's pitch: pre-train a VLA on <b>100,000 hours</b> of embodiment-free UMI trajectories spanning 1,700+ scenarios, auto-labeled by a VLM pipeline that describes scene-state transitions per clip; post-train on 7,200 hours of in-home real-robot data plus cross-embodiment mixes; obtain a foundation policy that adapts to new tasks from a few hours of demos. Reported results are strong: 75% success at &lt;10h of demos per task vs π0.5's 40%, and SOTA on four sim benchmarks. Before anything else, we resolved a confusing surface inconsistency — the abstract, the project page, and the paper body quote <i>different</i> headline numbers:</p>

<table>
  <colgroup><col width="150"/><col width="150"/><col width="150"/><col width="300"/></colgroup>
  <thead><tr><th background-color="light-gray">Benchmark</th><th background-color="light-gray">Abstract says</th><th background-color="light-gray">Project page says</th><th background-color="light-gray">What it actually is</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>RoboDojo</td><td>20.07 vs 13.07</td><td>13.93 vs 8.80</td><td>Same table, two metrics. RoboDojo reports <b>score / success-rate</b> pairs; the abstract quotes average score, the page quotes average SR. Table 5 gives both: XR-1 = 20.07/13.93, Hy-Embodied-0.5-VLA = 13.07/8.80. All baselines match the public leaderboard exactly.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>RoboCasa365</td><td>57.6 (v1) / 57.4 (v2)</td><td>57.4</td><td>v1→v2 editing artifact; the v2 intro still carries a stray "57.6". The official robocasa.ai leaderboard (updated 2026-07-21) lists XR-1 at <b>57.4, rank #1</b> — benchmark-maintainer-verified.</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<p>So the benchmark claims hold up to external scrutiny. The scaling claims are another matter. Three findings from our audit:</p>

<p><b>1. Every scaling curve stops at ~20K hours — one fifth of the title number.</b> Figures 5 and 8 sweep data fractions of a ~20K-hour UMI subset (2.5K→20K) and model sizes 2.6B→10.5B. The "no saturation" claim rests on three doublings whose marginal post-train gains are already <i>declining</i> (+27, +16, +6pp). The 20K→100K leap — the paper's entire premise — is a 5× unvalidated extrapolation: the 100K model appears only in benchmark tables, never in a scaling curve.</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:xiaomi:pretrain-scaling]]</p>

<p><b>2. The smooth monotonic improvement is an averaging artifact.</b> We digitized Fig. 8's bars: per-task scaling is visibly non-monotonic — Shoe Storage hits 83% at 50% data vs 75% at 100%; Sofa Tidying scores 80% at 5B vs 77% at 10B. The clean "Average" column hides regressions on individual tasks, and trial counts per bar are never stated.</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:xiaomi:posttrain-scaling]]</p>

<p><b>3. The auto-labeling pipeline — called "crucial" in the abstract — is completely unablated.</b> What the paper discloses: fixed-length clips (length never stated), Qwen3.5-27B writing structured <code>Gripper:/Object:{state-change}</code> captions, ~2 weeks of processing for 100K hours. No verification pass, no failure-mode analysis, and no label-granularity-vs-scale ablation — meaning conditioning quality and data scale are fully confounded at every scaling point. The downstream instruction-alignment stage exists precisely because these auto-labels are <i>not</i> natural instructions, which is itself telling.</p>

<p>Two more things worth knowing. First, the lineage: we verified against the open XR-0 codebase that XR-1 is the <b>same architecture</b> (Qwen3-VL + DiT mixture-of-transformers, verbatim noise schedule and 5-step Euler integrator) with a new data recipe; the one genuinely new mechanism is a Choice-Policies auxiliary loss fixing a copy shortcut where the DiT attends to the VLM's action tokens. Second, the Fermi check: 100K UMI hours implies roughly 60–270 full-time collectors for a year, 180–720TB of video, and O(100) inference GPUs for labeling — about 10× RDT2's 10K hours, the largest <i>open</i> UMI corpus. This is an industrial moat, not a recipe a lab can follow. And the reproducibility verdict as of today: repo is README+PDF (246 stars), no weights anywhere, and the real-robot adaptation claims rest on ~10 trials per task (±13pp CIs) with private data. Buried caveat worth surfacing: XR-1 <i>loses</i> RoboDojo's Memory dimension (7.81 vs 13.37) because it observes no history — and the human teleop reference on RoboDojo is 80.4, so 20.07 is SOTA but far from human.</p>

