<h1>Video models as robot-facing world models</h1>

<p>Two papers this week ask what a video foundation model can <i>do</i> for robotics beyond pretty rollouts. One proposes a control interface; the other audits whether any of these models understand physics. Our probe of the first found real substance in the weights — and a headline number that needs an asterisk.</p>

<h2>Masked Visual Actions: a 15-hour LoRA control interface — we read the weights to find where it lives</h2>
<p>Alzayer, Huang et al. (Stanford/UMD/Harvard, 2026) · <a href="https://huggingface.co/papers/2607.19343">HF</a> · <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2607.19343">PDF</a> · <a href="https://masked-visual-actions.github.io/">Project</a> · <a href="https://github.com/HadiZayer/masked-visual-actions">Code</a> · <a href="https://huggingface.co/HadiZayer/masked-visual-actions">Weights</a></p>

<p>The idea: express action as a <b>partially revealed trajectory in pixel space</b>. Reveal the robot's motion and the video model becomes a forward dynamics model predicting the scene's response; reveal the desired <i>object</i> motion and the same checkpoint recovers robot behavior consistent with that outcome. One 15-hour finetune of Wan2.2-Fun-A14B-Control, one checkpoint, three downstream uses (planning by ranking candidate futures, policy evaluation, action extraction).</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:mva:interface]]</p>

<p>Reading the released code and pinned DiffSynth-Studio pipeline source told us what the paper's prose does not: <b>there is no mask channel</b>. A masked visual action is an ordinary RGB video fed through the base model's native <code>control_video</code> input — VAE-encoded and channel-concatenated with the noisy latents, with the reference first frame prepended as an extra token frame. The mask exists only implicitly in pixel space (unrevealed = uniform gray; revealed entity keeps its pixels), built by SAM cut-outs ("A robotic arm") or translucent URDF renders with bright-red gripper fingers. The released <code>infer.py</code> exercises only the forward direction; inverse modeling from object masks is claimed zero-shot, and the renderer that makes the control videos is "coming soon."</p>

<p>We then probed the released LoRA weights directly (both experts, 2.45GB each, SHA256 recorded). The adapters are <b>fat</b> — rank 256 across all 40 blocks, 1.23B params per expert, ~8.8% of the 14B expert — and their structure is informative:</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:mva:lora-norms]]</p>

<p>Per-block update norms peak at DiT blocks 2–3 (~165) and decay monotonically to ~12 at block 39, in both experts: <b>the interface lives in the early blocks</b>, where the control channel is first fused. And the high-noise expert (which handles global structure) rewires <code>cross_attn.k/q</code> hardest — the text pathway being subordinated to the visual control channel — while high/low profiles correlate at r=0.912. This is the kind of fact you cannot get from the paper: the "15-hour finetune" is not a light touch, it is a targeted rewiring of the model's conditioning front-end.</p>

<p>The headline downstream claim needs scrutiny. The r=0.982 correlation between imagined-rollout outcomes and real execution is <b>7 task-level points from a single open-loop Diffusion Policy</b> on RoboCasa (10 rollouts per scene, manual rubric) — a correlation across per-task success rates, not a rank correlation across policies or checkpoints, with acknowledged positive bias. The planning gains (+7–26%, Best-of-10, Gemini-judged with a genuinely careful anti-hallucination protocol in the appendix) are actually the stronger evidence. And the 90% action-extraction number comes with a favorable setup: baselines only see the first generated frame. Our verdict: a clever, honest engineering result — a cross-embodiment control interface for the price of a LoRA — but "world model for policy evaluation" is oversold on seven points. Local reproduction is blocked precisely: ~67GB of bf16 weights vs a 16GB card, and DiffSynth disk-offload would stream ~2.8TB per 81-frame clip.</p>

