  </tbody>
</table>

<h1>The drift stack: four diagnoses of long-horizon world-model decay</h1>

<p>Three papers in one week attack the same problem — autoregressive video world models drift off-distribution in long closed-loop rollouts — and each blames a different layer of the stack. Read together they form a coherent taxonomy rather than competing claims, so we investigated them as one thread.</p>

<h2>ABot-World-0 × AlayaWorld × Self Gradient Forcing: same problem, four layers, composable fixes</h2>
<p>Jiang et al. / AlayaWorld Team / Zhuang et al. (2026) · <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2607.19191">ABot PDF</a> · <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2607.18367">AlayaWorld PDF</a> · <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2607.20368">SGF PDF</a> · <a href="https://github.com/amap-cvlab/ABot-World">ABot Code</a> · <a href="https://github.com/AlayaLab/AlayaWorld">AlayaWorld Code</a> · <a href="https://github.com/zhuang2002/Self_Gradient_Forcing">SGF Code</a></p>

<p>All three inherit the shared baseline: <b>Self Forcing</b> fixes exposure bias by training on the model's own rollouts scored by distribution-matching distillation. None claims to improve on that layer. What each adds:</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:drift:taxonomy]]</p>

<p><b>AlayaWorld</b> diagnoses a <i>context-quality gap</i>: the model cannot recover from its own degraded past. Its fix is corrupted-history training — Helios-style latent corruptions (noise/blur/saturation) plus an <b>error bank</b> of its own reconstruction residuals, bucketed by chunk length and noise level — applied to temporal and spatial-memory tokens while the sink frame stays clean. <b>SGF</b> diagnoses a subtler <i>memory-writing gradient gap</i>: in vanilla Self Forcing the history KV cache is frozen rollout state, so future losses supervise cache <i>reading</i> but never cache <i>writing</i> — the clean-timestep K/V formation drifts as shared DiT parameters update. The fix is a two-pass scheme that re-opens gradients through context K/V formation without backpropagating the serial rollout:</p>

<pre lang="python" caption="SGF two-pass training (reconstructed from the paper's algorithm)"><code># Pass 1: no-grad autoregressive rollout, exactly matching inference
with torch.no_grad():
    ctx, noisy = rollout_to_exit_step(model, prompt)   # self-generated context + exit-step latents

# Pass 2: parallel context-gradient reconstruction at the recorded exit step
ctx_sg = ctx.detach()                # generated context as stop-gradient CLEAN latents
kv = model.encode_kv(ctx_sg)         # gradients flow through HOW context becomes K/V
loss = mse(model.denoise(noisy, kv=kv), target)   # future losses supervise memory-writing
loss.backward()                      # +13% wall-clock; direct differentiable cache OOMs</code></pre>

<p><b>ABot-World-0</b> diagnoses a <i>teacher-horizon mismatch</i>: the distillation teacher only demonstrates short horizons, so long student rollouts have no supervision target. LongForcing runs the final DMD stage on <i>long</i> student self-rollouts against an <i>extended-horizon</i> teacher — and the paper explicitly rejects the over-anchoring alternative (sinks "delay" drift but lock the scene).</p>

<p><b>Composability — the actionable result.</b> SGF vs corrupted-history training is cleanly orthogonal (memory encoding vs input robustness). LongForcing overlaps with corrupted-history in effect (self-rollout DMD implicitly trains on imperfect context) but neither subsumes the other — corrupted-history is teacher-free and explicitly teaches <i>recovery</i>. And bolting SGF onto the others: clean for ABot (chunk-wise causal DiT with sink+FIFO KV cache is exactly SGF's evaluated geometry), partial for AlayaWorld (its H_φ history compressor and non-differentiable depth-warped spatial memory sit outside SGF's gradient picture).</p>

<p><b>Evidence quality, ranked.</b> ABot is the only paper with actual <i>drift curves</i> — four metrics vs time over 60s — but they are self-baseline-only and stop at one minute. SGF is the best-controlled (matched init/seed/geometry, 5s training window extrapolating to 240s, &gt;1,900 human GSB judgments) but reports endpoints only and is non-interactive. AlayaWorld has the broadest benchmark (iWorld-Bench, big margins on drift-sensitive metrics) but never states the horizon and shows no curves. The common gap is stark: <b>nobody quantifies identity or controllability decay at 10–60 minutes</b>, which is the regime "interactive world model" actually promises.</p>

<p><b>Artifact status today (all verified).</b> ABot ships code (883★) and 5B weights that run at 720p/16FPS in 19.3GiB — a 24GB consumer card suffices. AlayaWorld ships inference code and 33.6GB of weights under LTX-2's <b>non-commercial</b> license, with gated dependencies (Gemma-3-12B, DA3-Giant). SGF shipped full training+inference code and checkpoints <i>the same day as the paper</i>; inference is desktop-feasible (Wan2.1-1.3B scale), training wants ~87GB. For a lab with one good GPU, the buildable path is ABot weights now, SGF's two-pass when you next train.</p>

