<h1>Harnesses as optimizable artifacts</h1>

<p>A quieter thread in the pool: the agent harness itself is becoming a first-class thing to optimize, not fixed scaffolding. Three papers worth noticing, none deep-dived this run.</p>

<table>
  <colgroup><col width="200"/><col width="230"/><col width="230"/><col width="90"/></colgroup>
  <thead><tr><th background-color="light-gray">Paper</th><th background-color="light-gray">Key Contribution</th><th background-color="light-gray">Why It Matters</th><th background-color="light-gray">Links</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td><b>Recursive Harness Self-Improvement</b> (2026)</td><td>Treats the agent harness as an optimizable prompt-level artifact; a few RHI iterations beat max-reasoning-effort baselines at ~60% lower inference cost.</td><td>Directly adjacent to heuristic-learning ideas: the open question is whether learned harnesses transfer across task families or are per-task prompt overfitting.</td><td><a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2607.15524">PDF</a></td></tr>
    <tr><td><b>FlashRT</b> (2026)</td><td>Coding-agent harness that lifts reference implementations of real-time multimodal systems (incl. video world models) into optimized multi-GPU deployments; up to 70× latency cut, beats vLLM-Omni on AMD.</td><td>Agent-driven systems optimization aimed at exactly the world-model workloads above; the chain-of-program IR + measurement-gated loop is an inspectable design.</td><td><a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2607.18171">PDF</a></td></tr>
    <tr><td><b>NexForge</b> (2026)</td><td>Requirement-driven synthesis of executable agent tasks; lifts an open 35B-A3B model to 75.3% Terminal-Bench 2.1 (SOTA open-source); models public.</td><td>Task synthesis as the lever for agent capability — complements RHI's harness-level optimization from the data side.</td><td><a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2607.14186">PDF</a></td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<h1>Cross-cutting observations</h1>

<p><b>The release gap split cleanly this week.</b> We verified artifact status for every deep-dive paper: ABot-World-0 (code+weights), AlayaWorld (code+weights, non-commercial), SGF (full code+checkpoints, same-day), Masked Visual Actions (inference code + both LoRAs; renderer, data, and eval code missing) all shipped <i>something</i> usable. The biggest claim of the week — Xiaomi's 100K hours — shipped a README and a PDF. The pattern is becoming reliable: the more industrial the result, the thinner the artifact. Plan your reading time accordingly.</p>

<p><b>Evidence quality is the bottleneck, not ideas.</b> Xiaomi's scaling thesis rests on a 5× extrapolation past the last measured point; MVA's policy-evaluation claim rests on 7 correlation points; every drift paper stops measuring at 60–240 seconds while promising open-ended interaction. All three threads had a good idea <i>and</i> a gap between the idea and its demonstration. The most useful community contribution right now would not be another mechanism — it would be a shared, long-horizon, identity-and-controllability benchmark that runs for an hour.</p>
